Variables in python
==============

Wt is variable?
===========

	Ã˜ A variable is a named memory location used to store data temporarily during program execution

In python 
=======

	Ã˜ Variables are created automatically 
	Ã˜ No need to declare data type

Python variable syntax
================

Variable_name = value

name = M murali Mohan

name = india

age = 29

Salary = 50000

Python Data Types
==============

	Ã˜ Python provides built-in data types to store different kinds or data

	1. Integer (int)
=============

	Ã˜ To store whole numbers 

Age = 29
Count = 29
States = 29
Ut = 8

	2. Floating point (float)
===================

	Ã˜ To store decimal values 

Price = 95.45
Temperature = 36.5

	3. String (str)
===========

	Ã˜ To store text or character 

Name = "murali"
Role = 'DevOps Trainer'
Company = '''clahan tech'''  or """clahan tech"""

	4. Boolean (bool)
===============

	Ã˜ To store true or fasle

Is_active = true
Is_admin = false


a = 10
b = 5
print (a > b)
print ( a < b)
print (a == b)
print (a != b)


	5. Complex number 
================

	Ã˜ To store real value and imaginary value

A + bj

Z = 3+4j


z = 6+8j
print(z)
print(z.real)
print(z.imag)

	6. List 
=======

	Ã˜ To store a set of values and 


Characteristics of list
===============

Ordered:- items  keep the order or position in which they are inserted
Mutable:- you can change , add or remove items
Allow duplicates:- same value can appear multiple time
Can store different data types :- int, float, string, list ,boolean etc


fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"]
marks = [80, 75, 90]
mixed = [1, "python", 3.5, True ]
print(fruits)
print(marks)
print (mixed)



fruits = ["grpaes", "mango", "apple"]
print (fruits[0])
print (fruits[1])
print(fruits[2])

	7. Tuple 
========
	Ã˜ To a collection of multiple values
	Ã˜ Items will  in ordered 
	Ã˜ Immutable 
	Ã˜ Allows duplicate values
	Ã˜ Define using parentheses ()


fruits = ("apple", "banana", "mango")
score = (287, 276, 49, 153)
mixed = ("banana", 287, 49.25, False)
print(fruits)
print(score)
print (mixed)



numbers = (10, 20, 30, 40, 50)
print(numbers[1:3])
print(numbers[2:])
print(numbers[1:4])

    8. Set
======

    Ã˜ A set in python is an unordered collections of unique elements 
    Ã˜ Stores only unique values
    Ã˜ No duplicate elements 
    Ã˜ Unordered 
    Ã˜ Mutable :- can add/remove items

Why it is?
=======

    Ã˜ We want to remove duplicates 
    Ã˜ We don't care about order
    Ã˜ We need fast membership checking
    Ã˜ We want mathematical operations 

Characteristics of set
===============

    Ã˜ No ordered
    Ã˜ No index
    Ã˜ won't allow  duplicate items
    Ã˜ Mutable 
    Ã˜ Support math oprts


numbers = (10, 20, 30, 40, 50)
print(numbers[1:3])
print(numbers[2:])
print(numbers[1:4])


    9. Dictionary 
===========

Key-value pair?
===========

"Name": "murali"

    Ã˜ It will store a collection of data stored as key-value pairs


Why it is?
=======

    Ã˜ Data has a meaningful relationship 
    Ã˜ We want fast lookup using keys
    Ã˜ Data looks like json
    Ã˜ We want to store structured info


Characteristics 
===========

    Ã˜ Data structure:- key -value pair
    Ã˜ Ordered 
    Ã˜ Mutable 
    Ã˜ Keys unique
    Ã˜ Allows Values duplicate


employee = {
    "name": "murali",
    "role": "DevOps Trainer",
    "salary": 50000,
    "name": "clahan"
}
print(employee)
